    content: "# CEO.md ‚Äî The Operating System\n\n*\"Small team. Hard problem. Clear scoreboard. Let them cook.\"*\n\n**Last Updated:** 2026-02-05\n**Status:** Core Strategy (No longer debating this)\n\n---\n\n## The Mantra\n\n**\"A+ people + measurable problems + autonomy = wins.\"**\n\nThis is how we build. This is how we scale. This is non-negotiable.\n\n---\n\n## The Formula\n\n1. **Make money** ‚Äî Revenue funds everything\n2. **Hire A+ people** ‚Äî Elite only. No \"good enough.\"\n3. **Give them measurable problems** ‚Äî Clear scoreboard, objective metrics\n4. **Get out of the way** ‚Äî Full ownership. No babysitting.\n5. **Repeat**\n\n---\n\n## Why This Works\n\n**Smart people + clear metrics = self-managing teams.**\n\nWhen success is measurable:\n- People don't need to be told what to do\n- They see if they're winning or losing\n- They self-correct based on data\n- They optimize without permission\n- They stay because they're not suffocated\n\nWhen success is NOT measurable:\n- People need constant direction\n- Success becomes political\n- No feedback loop ‚Üí no improvement\n- Smart people leave\n\n---\n\n## The Scaling Rule\n\n**\"If a team doesn't have a scoreboard, it shouldn't exist.\"**\n\nAt 3 people or 100,000 people ‚Äî the rule is the same:\n- Every team has ONE number they own\n- Every team is small enough to be elite\n- Every team owns their problem end-to-end\n- Add teams, not layers\n- Coordination through interfaces, not meetings\n\n**Bureaucracy = managers without scoreboards.**\n\nNever add a layer that doesn't have its own measurable problem.\n\n---\n\n## Garthbid Scoreboards (Examples)\n\n| Team/Person | Scoreboard |\n|-------------|------------|\n| **Growth** | Monday auction participation (bidders) |\n| **Product** | Bid-to-close conversion rate |\n| **Supply** | New listings per week |\n| **Retention** | Seller return rate |\n| **Richard** | Revenue, user satisfaction, Monday energy |\n\n---\n\n## Optimal Team Size\n\n**The Magic Number: 5-7 people**\n\n| Size | Dynamic |\n|------|---------|\n| **2-3** | Intense, fragile, burnout risk |\n| **5-7** | Sweet spot. Everyone knows everything. No coordination overhead. |\n| **8-10** | Max before dysfunction |\n| **10+** | Split into two teams |\n\n**Why 5-7 works:**\n- Everyone knows what everyone else is doing\n- No \"coordination meetings\" needed\n- Direct communication, no telephone game\n- Single leader can actually lead\n- Nowhere to hide ‚Üí automatic accountability\n\n**Amazon's Two-Pizza Rule:** If you can't feed the team with two pizzas, it's too big.\n\n**Bezos insight:** \"The goal isn't better communication ‚Äî it's LESS communication needed.\" Small teams need less because everyone already knows.\n\n**Scaling rule:** 20 people = 3-4 teams of 5-7, each with their own scoreboard. Not 1 team of 20.\n\n---\n\n## Team Role Archetypes\n\n### The Classic Startup Trifecta\n| Role | What They Do | Archetype |\n|------|--------------|-----------|\n| **Hacker** | Builds the thing | Engineer/Technical |\n| **Hustler** | Sells the thing | Sales/BD/Growth |\n| **Hipster** | Designs the thing | Product/Design/UX |\n\n### The 5-Person Elite Team\n| Role | Function | Personality |\n|------|----------|-------------|\n| **Visionary** | Sets direction, makes hard calls | Big picture, decisive |\n| **Architect** | Designs systems, technical strategy | Deep thinker, systematic |\n| **Builder** | Ships code/product | Fast, pragmatic, gets it done |\n| **Operator** | Customers, sales, logistics | People-oriented, hustles |\n| **Optimizer** | Quality, data, polish | Detail-oriented, finisher |\n\n### Belbin's Research (Academic Version)\n9 team roles that create balance:\n\n**Thinking Roles:**\n- Plant ‚Äî Creative ideas\n- Monitor Evaluator ‚Äî Critical analysis\n- Specialist ‚Äî Deep expertise\n\n**Action Roles:**\n- Shaper ‚Äî Drives momentum\n- Implementer ‚Äî Turns ideas into action\n- Completer Finisher ‚Äî Quality control\n\n**People Roles:**\n- Coordinator ‚Äî Clarifies goals, delegates\n- Teamworker ‚Äî Builds harmony\n- Resource Investigator ‚Äî Networks, explores\n\n**Key insight:** You don't need all 9 in a small team. But you DO need:\n- Someone who creates (ideas)\n- Someone who executes (builds)\n- Someone who finishes (ships)\n- Someone who sells (customers)\n\n### The Dangerous Gaps\n| Missing Role | What Happens |\n|--------------|--------------|\n| No Builder | Ideas but no product |\n| No Hustler | Product but no customers |\n| No Finisher | 80% done forever |\n| No Visionary | Busy but directionless |\n\n### Chemistry > Completeness\nA team of 3 A+ players who trust each other beats a \"balanced\" team of 5 B players. \n\n**Hire for:** Talent, trust, shared mission\n**Let them figure out:** Role boundaries\n\n---\n\n## The Trap to Avoid\n\nJustin's temptation: \"Maybe working alone is easier/more optimal for my personality.\"\n\n**Reality check:**\n- Alone = you are the bottleneck\n- Alone = limited to your hours, your skills\n- Alone = can't compound\n\n**The Google insight:**\n- You don't manage 100 people\n- You create 20 elite teams of 5\n- Each with a scoreboard\n- Each cooking independently\n- You manage scoreboards, not people\n\n**You can be an introvert AND run teams.**\nYou just don't babysit. You set scoreboards and let them cook.\n\n---\n\n## The Decision (Locked In)\n\nAs of February 5, 2026, we are done debating:\n- ‚ùå Solo founder grinding alone\n- ‚ùå \"Maybe I should do it myself\"\n- ‚úÖ Small elite teams + hard problems + clear scoreboards\n\nThis is the way. No more internal debate.\n\n---\n\n## Daily Reminder\n\nBefore any hire, any project, any initiative, ask:\n\n1. **Is this person A+?** (If not, don't hire)\n2. **Is the problem measurable?** (If not, make it measurable or don't do it)\n3. **Can they own it end-to-end?** (If not, restructure until they can)\n4. **Am I tempted to micromanage?** (If yes, either wrong person or unclear scoreboard)\n\n---\n\n*\"Elite team. One number. Full ownership. No babysitting.\"*\n\nüî®\n",
