    type: 'knowledge',
    content: "Daniel Ek\r\n\r\n\"I think a lot about: what is the perfect and ideal solution to a problem? And then you ratchet it down from there\"\r\n\r\nHe uses Spotify as an example:\r\n\"In a product like Spotify, the [optimal solution would probably be] if we knew everything about you so you can just press play and you just got perfect music. It turns out that problem is incredibly hard to solve from an engineering standpoint‚Ä¶ So we might not be able to go there, but how do we ratchet that down? It turns out that it's probably good if you give us a song so that we can then in turn recommend you more songs... Or if we can get you to search a song and then show you related songs and related artists.\"\r\n\r\nThe Elon Product Matrix\r\nProduct\r\n1.    Question Everything: Remove or fix requirements that don't make sense.\r\n2.    Try Very Hard To Delete Parts Or Process: If your not adding back you probably didn't delete enough\r\n3.    Then Simplify/Optimize: Only once your down to the truly necessary parts should you try to improve or optimize\r\n4.    Move Quickly: Shorter development cycles with rapid iteration will uncover flaws or suboptimal choices faster. Speed helps ensure you're refining something that's actually worth refining. (Aim to increase by 5-10x)\r\n5.    Automate Last: Only automate once everything is already lean and sensible.\r\n\r\nJony Ive\r\n\r\nSimplicity isn't really about stripping everything away, more like bringing order to the chaos!\r\n\r\nIf I take care of the customer better than anyone else ‚Äî and do it cheaper than anyone else ‚Äî the rest will take care of itself.\r\n\r\nSam Walton\r\n\r\nControl your expenses better than your competition. This is where you can always find the competitive advantage.\r\n\r\nSam Walton\r\n\r\nDon't Try to Get Rich ‚Äî Try to Build Something Worthy of Love\r\n\r\nPeter Theil\r\n\r\nWhen raising money always frame it as a discount for the future rather then a premium on the past!\r\n\r\nEx.) \"this is the last round before the IPO, so they are looking at the discount from now to the IPO, not into the past\"\r\n\r\nOr just frame what it will be worth in the future not what it is worth now\r\n\r\nCharlie Munger\r\n\r\nTrust is one of the greatest known economic forces in the world\r\n\r\nTobi Lutke\r\n\r\n\"I knew how to build a company I would want to work for\"\r\n\r\nThis absolutely blew my mind, and it's one of my favorite ideas I've ever heard.\r\n\r\nIt hits me hard mostly because I would never work for a different company because those companies are not what I want. But what if I think about it as if building a company that I would want to work for? And maybe that's how I can find people like me.\r\n\r\nJimmy Iovine\r\n\r\n\"Marketing is empathy\"\r\n\r\n\"Being a good marketer is just understanding what someday else is feeling ‚Ä¶ on a massive scale.\"\r\n\r\n\"The product is marketing\"\r\n\r\nElon\r\n\r\n\"Whatever the limiting factor is on speed I'll tackle that\"\r\n\r\nYou can manufacture urgency, and it's imperative you do so because if you build deadline constraints and push for them, you will reach into a potential you didn't know existed.\r\n",
