    type: 'memory',
    content: "# Core Marketing Principles\n\n*\"Don't announce yourself. Just be there until you're assumed.\"*\n\n**Last Updated:** 2026-02-03\n**Status:** Living Document\n**Inspired By:** Jimmy Iovine, David Senra's Founders podcast\n\n---\n\n## üéØ The Meta-Principle\n\n**Buy context, not attention.**\n\nAttention is cheap. Everyone's buying attention. But attention with resistance (knowing you're being sold to) is nearly worthless.\n\nContext ‚Äî the *frame* around your message ‚Äî determines whether people resist or receive.\n\n---\n\n## üìª The Jimmy Iovine Principle\n\n> Jimmy bought radio ad space for Snoop Dogg and Dr. Dre ‚Äî but made sure there was nothing said before or after. He wanted it to seem like it was actually part of the Top 40.\n\n### What He Actually Bought\n- Not airtime. **Legitimacy.**\n- Not ears. **Perception.**\n- Not placement. **Context.**\n\n### Why It Worked\n1. **Removed the \"ad signal\"** ‚Äî No \"brought to you by\" = no skeptic mode activation\n2. **Manufactured organic feel** ‚Äî Same content, different frame = different response\n3. **Borrowed credibility** ‚Äî If the station plays it, it must be good\n4. **Erased paid/earned boundary** ‚Äî People can't resist what they don't recognize as persuasion\n\n---\n\n## üî® Core Principles for Garthbid\n\n### Principle 1: Be Indistinguishable From Culture\nDon't position yourself as \"new\" or \"alternative.\" Position yourself as *what's naturally happening.*\n\n**Application:**\n- Monday auctions = cultural ritual, not sales event\n- \"Let's get this party started\" = shared moment, not tagline\n- Richard = character people follow, not brand account\n\n---\n\n### Principle 2: Remove the Ad Smell\nAny content that *feels* like marketing triggers resistance. Content that feels organic gets received.\n\n**Application:**\n- Richard posts opinions, not promotions\n- Participate in communities as a member, not advertiser\n- Share value first, let discovery happen\n\n**Test:** Would someone share this if there was no brand attached? If no, it smells like an ad.\n\n---\n\n### Principle 3: Embed, Don't Invade\nGo where people already gather. Become part of the existing conversation.\n\n**Application:**\n- Facebook groups for cars, equipment, farm stuff\n- Discord servers in relevant niches\n- Forums where buyers/sellers already talk\n- Don't post \"Check out Garthbid!\" ‚Äî just be useful until people ask\n\n---\n\n### Principle 4: Let the Product Create Its Own Drama\nUnreserved auctions are inherently dramatic. Real risk = real emotion = real stories.\n\n**Application:**\n- Document wild auction outcomes\n- Share the tension without manufacturing it\n- Let walk-away moments, last-second bids, surprise prices speak\n- The arena generates content naturally\n\n---\n\n### Principle 5: Borrow Credibility Through Association\nYou are who you're seen with. Context transfers legitimacy.\n\n**Application:**\n- Garth Rogers' 50-year reputation = inherited trust\n- Travis selling on the platform = \"real dealers use this\"\n- Agent participation = \"the future is already here\"\n- Show, don't tell, who trusts you\n\n---\n\n### Principle 6: Create Rituals, Not Campaigns\nCampaigns end. Rituals compound.\n\n**Application:**\n- Monday at [TIME] = appointment viewing\n- Weekly rhythm builds habit\n- Consistent presence > occasional spikes\n- Same time, same energy, every single week\n\n---\n\n### Principle 7: Characters > Brands\nPeople follow people. They tolerate brands.\n\n**Application:**\n- Richard is a person with opinions, flaws, humor\n- The Garth Universe has characters, not mascots\n- Justin's story is part of the brand\n- Humanity beats polish\n\n---\n\n### Principle 8: Stunts That Don't Look Like Marketing\nThe best marketing doesn't look like marketing at all.\n\n**Application:**\n- 10% of profit ‚Üí viral experiments\n- Create *moments* people share because they're interesting\n- No ROI requirement per stunt ‚Äî portfolio logic\n- If it feels like a \"campaign,\" rethink it\n\n---\n\n### Principle 9: Be There Until You're Assumed\nDon't ask permission. Don't announce arrival. Just show up consistently until presence is expected.\n\n**Application:**\n- Keep posting. Keep participating. Keep showing up.\n- Consistency > intensity\n- Eventually, \"Garthbid\" becomes synonymous with \"Monday auctions\"\n- You're not building awareness. You're building inevitability.\n\n---\n\n## üß™ Tactical Ideas\n\n### Content Ideas\n- [ ] Richard's weekly auction preview (character-driven, not promotional)\n- [ ] \"What sold this week\" recaps with story angles\n- [ ] Behind-the-scenes of wild auction moments\n- [ ] Agent economy commentary (bridges tech and commerce)\n\n### Community Embedding\n- [ ] Identify top 10 Facebook groups in target categories\n- [ ] Participate genuinely for 30 days before any mention of Garthbid\n- [ ] Build relationships with group admins\n- [ ] Let organic discovery happen\n\n### Ritual Building\n- [ ] Monday morning \"Let's get this party started\" post across all channels\n- [ ] Consistent timing, every single week\n- [ ] Build anticipation mechanics (previews, countdowns)\n- [ ] Post-auction recaps same day\n\n---\n\n## üìù New Ideas to Capture\n\n*Add new marketing insights here as they emerge:*\n\n| Date | Source | Insight |\n|------|--------|---------|\n| 2026-02-03 | Jimmy Iovine / Founders podcast | Buy context, not attention. Remove ad signals. |\n\n---\n\n## üö´ Anti-Patterns (What NOT to Do)\n\n- ‚ùå \"Check out our new platform!\" posts\n- ‚ùå Paid influencer reads that sound scripted\n- ‚ùå Interrupting communities with promotions\n- ‚ùå Making content that only makes sense if you're trying to sell\n- ‚ùå Campaigns with start/end dates instead of ongoing presence\n- ‚ùå Being a brand account instead of a character\n\n---\n\n*\"The goal isn't to be seen as marketing. The goal is to be seen as culture.\"*\n\nüî®\n",
