    id: 'product-roadmap-learn-stuff',
    name: 'learn-stuff.md',
    path: '/product-roadmap/learn-stuff.md',
    type: 'knowledge',
    content: "Study and implement\r\n\r\nhttps://vercel.com/blog/introducing-react-best-practices\r\n\r\nAlso find some good resources to learn for backend\r\n\r\nYes ‚Äî there are similar \"best practices\" resources for backend developers. They don't always live in one big curated blog like the Vercel React one, but there are well-organized checklists, architectures, and security/performance guidelines you can follow:\r\n\r\nüìå Repositories & Framework-Style Guides\r\n    ‚Ä¢    GitHub collections of backend practices ‚Äî e.g., backend-best-practices repos that gather patterns, conventions, and code organization tips in one place (similar to React Best Practices, but for backends).\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Futurice backend best practices ‚Äî evolving guidelines on things like credential storage, throttling, logging, and general security measures.\r\n\r\nThese are structured and community-maintained, so you can adopt or adapt them based on your stack (Node, Python, Go, etc.).\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nüîê Security Best Practices (as a core backend theme)\r\n\r\nBackend systems must embed security into design ‚Äî not as an afterthought: secure-by-design is a recognized concept.\r\n\r\nCommon backend security practices include:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Validate and sanitize every input.\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Use HTTPS/TLS everywhere.\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Implement proper auth and access control (JWT, OAuth, RBAC).\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Parameterize DB queries to avoid injection attacks.\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Secure session/cookie handling and rate limits.\r\n\r\nThe OWASP Secure Coding Practices Checklist is especially comprehensive if you want a standardized, detailed checklist.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n‚öôÔ∏è Performance & Scalability\r\n\r\nBackend best practices also cover performance and scalability, such as:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Efficient database indexing and query optimization.\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Caching frequently read data.\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Load balancing and asynchronous workflows for heavy workloads.\r\n\r\nThese recommendations appear in many curated guides and roadmaps for backend devs.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nüìã Comprehensive Checklists & Roadmaps\r\n\r\nThere are ultimate checklists listing key skills and practices for backend engineers, covering: HTTP basics, frameworks, DB management, API design, auth, error handling, testing, and deployment.\r\n\r\nThey work like a backend \"best practices curriculum\" you can follow to level up systematically.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nüß† Quick Example: A Minimal Best Practices Outline for Backends\r\n    1.    Architecture: modular, clear separation of concerns.\r\n    2.    Security: HTTPS, input validation, auth & access control.\r\n    3.    DB: normalized schema, indexes, backups, caching.\r\n    4.    Performance: async tasks, caching, profiling & monitoring.\r\n    5.    Testing & CI/CD: automated tests & pipeline automation.\r\n    6.    Documentation & code quality: linting, reviews, clear API docs.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can point you to specific GitHub repos or checklists for your backend stack (e.g., Node.js, Python/Django, Go, Java/Spring). Just tell me your tech stack!\r\n\r\nAnd learn Redis\r\n\r\nYes ‚Äî and Redis actually has excellent \"best-practice-style\" learning paths if you know where to look.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nüîë The best Redis learning resources (ranked)\r\n\r\n1. Redis Official Docs (the gold standard)\r\n\r\nWhy it's great\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Clear mental models (in-memory, single-threaded, atomic ops)\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Practical sections on when to use each data structure\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Real production trade-offs (latency, persistence, eviction)\r\n\r\nStart here:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Redis Data Types\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Persistence (RDB vs AOF)\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Eviction policies\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Transactions & Lua\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Redis as cache vs database\r\n\r\nüëâ This is Redis's equivalent of \"React best practices\".\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n2. Redis University (free, structured, excellent)\r\n\r\nWhat it gives you\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Hands-on labs\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Real use cases (rate limiting, queues, caching)\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Short, focused modules\r\n\r\nBest courses:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    RU101 ‚Äì Redis fundamentals\r\n    ‚Ä¢    RU202 ‚Äì Redis as a data platform\r\n    ‚Ä¢    RU301 ‚Äì Redis in production\r\n\r\nIf you want confidence, not vibes ‚Äî this is it.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n3. Redis in Action\r\n\r\nWhy it still matters\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Teaches thinking in Redis\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Shows real architectures (leaderboards, queues, sessions)\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Bridges theory ‚Üí production patterns\r\n\r\nThis book teaches judgment, not syntax.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n4. Designing Data-Intensive Applications (Redis chapters)\r\n\r\nWhy it's powerful\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Explains Redis in the context of:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    consistency\r\n    ‚Ä¢    durability\r\n    ‚Ä¢    replication\r\n    ‚Ä¢    failure modes\r\n\r\nThis is how senior backend engineers reason.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n5. GitHub \"Best Practices\" style repos\r\n\r\nLook for:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    redis-patterns\r\n    ‚Ä¢    awesome-redis\r\n    ‚Ä¢    redis-use-cases\r\n\r\nThese are like field notes from production.\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nüß† The Redis mental model (compress this)\r\n\r\nRedis is:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Memory-first\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Latency-obsessed\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Simple primitives ‚Üí complex systems\r\n\r\nIf you ask:\r\n\r\n\"Is Redis a database or cache?\"\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is:\r\n\r\n\"It's a weapon ‚Äî depends how you wield it.\"\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\n‚ö†Ô∏è The 5 Redis mistakes almost everyone makes\r\n    1.    Treating Redis like Postgres\r\n    2.    Ignoring eviction policies\r\n    3.    Overusing KEYS instead of SCAN\r\n    4.    Forgetting persistence trade-offs\r\n    5.    Using it everywhere instead of surgically\r\n\r\n‚∏ª\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can:\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Give you a Redis decision tree (when to use Redis vs DB)\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Map Redis patterns directly to your Garthbid stack\r\n    ‚Ä¢    Design a Redis architecture for auctions, snipers, rate limits, queues\r\n\r\nJust say the word.\r\n",
