    type: 'knowledge',
    content: "# The Unemployable Company\n\n*A company designed for people who could never work at a company.*\n\n---\n\n## The Insight\n\nThe best people are often unemployable.\n\nThey can't be bossed around. They need autonomy. They're chaotic, intense, weird in ways that HR departments hate. Normal companies filter them out.\n\n**If you build a structure that works for the unemployable, you get access to talent no one else can hire.**\n\n---\n\n## The Core Deal\n\n> \"We're not hiring you. We're betting on you.\"\n\n| Commitment | Freedom |\n|------------|---------|\n| 35 hours/week on company problems | Work when you want, how you want |\n| Clear scoreboard (measurable outcomes) | No managers, no check-ins, no permission |\n| Ship results | Everything else is yours |\n\n---\n\n## The Escape Hatch\n\nYou can build your own thing on the side. If it takes off, we help you scale it.\n\n| Your Side Project Revenue | What Happens |\n|---------------------------|--------------|\n| **$10k MRR** | Go 50/50 ‚Äî half company time, half your project |\n| **$50k MRR** | Go 25/75 ‚Äî mostly your project |\n| **$100k MRR** | Full pivot ‚Äî your project becomes your main thing |\n\n**Equity split when you pivot:**\n- You (Visionary): 25%\n- Your team: 5-10% each\n- The Garth Company: 30-40%\n\nWe fund it. You run it. Everyone wins.\n\n---\n\n## The Five Freedoms\n\n1. **Work on what matters to you** ‚Äî Half your time is yours\n2. **Total autonomy** ‚Äî Results matter, not how you get there\n3. **No managers** ‚Äî Scoreboards, not supervisors\n4. **Permission to be chaotic** ‚Äî 15 hours one day, 3 the next, who cares\n5. **Permission to be human** ‚Äî Shutdowns, weird schedules, no judgment\n\n---\n\n## Who This Is For\n\n‚úÖ Entrepreneurs who want infrastructure without giving up ownership\n‚úÖ Autonomy addicts who suffocate in normal jobs\n‚úÖ Chaotic geniuses who need flexibility\n‚úÖ Neurodiverse folks who need async, low-pressure environments\n‚úÖ Anyone who's been told they're \"too much\" or \"not a team player\"\n\n‚ùå People who need structure and direction\n‚ùå People who want to clock in and clock out\n‚ùå People who need a boss to tell them what to do\n\n---\n\n## Why It Works\n\n**For the company:**\n- Access to talent no one else can hire\n- Built-in innovation pipeline (side projects)\n- Loyalty through optionality (why leave when you can build here?)\n- A+ players attract A+ players\n\n**For the individual:**\n- Stability + freedom (rare combination)\n- Upside if your thing works\n- Community of other unemployables\n- No soul-crushing corporate BS\n\n---\n\n## The Culture\n\n**Async-first.** No \"always on.\" No Slack panic.\n\n**Output over hours.** Did you ship? Good. Don't care when.\n\n**Direct feedback.** No politics. Say the thing.\n\n**High trust.** We assume you're working. Don't make us check.\n\n**Weird is welcome.** Your quirks are features, not bugs.\n\n---\n\n## The Pitch\n\n> \"We don't want employees. We want partners who share infrastructure.\n>\n> Work on company problems 35 hours a week. Spend the rest building whatever you want. If your thing takes off, we'll fund it and you keep the upside.\n>\n> This is a company for people who could never work at a company.\"\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- How do we verify the 35 hours without micromanaging? (Probably: trust + outcomes)\n- How do we handle someone whose side project competes with company?\n- What's the vesting schedule for side-project equity?\n- How do we maintain shared mission when everyone has their own thing?\n\n---\n\n*\"Build a company you'd want to work at ‚Äî even if you'd never work at a company.\"*\n\nüî®\n",
